# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish component of the 1918 United Kingdom general election took place on 14 December 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the final United Kingdom general election to be held throughout Ireland, as the next election would happen following Irish independence.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It is a key moment in modern Irish history, seeing the overwhelming defeat of the moderate nationalist Irish Parliamentary Party (IPP), which had dominated the Irish political landscape since the 1880s, and a landslide victory for the radical Sinn Féin party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin had never previously stood in a general election, but had won six seats in by-elections in 1917–1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had vowed in its manifesto to establish an independent Irish Republic.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster, however, the Unionist Party was the most successful party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the elections, Sinn Féin's elected members refused to attend the British Parliament in Westminster (London), and instead formed a parliament in Dublin, the First Dáil Éireann ("Assembly of Ireland"), which declared Irish independence as a republic.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish War of Independence was conducted under this revolutionary government which sought international recognition, and set about the process of state-building.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The other parties elected in the election were invited by Sinn Féin to join in creating the Dáil Éireann, but declined and took up their seats at Westminster.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 a system called plural voting was in place in both Britain and Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting was a practice whereby one person might be able to vote multiple times in an election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Property and business owners could vote both in the constituency where their property lay and that in which they lived, if the two were different.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This system often resulted in one person being able to cast multiple votes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the newly formed Irish Free State this system was ended by the Electoral Act 1923 and was abolished in the UK by the Representation of the People Act 1948.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting remained in effect in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The 1918 election was held in the aftermath of World War I, the Easter Rising and the Conscription Crisis.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the first general election to be held after the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was thus the first election in which women over the age of 30, and all men over the age of 21, could vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Previously, all women and most working-class men had been excluded from voting.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 the whole of Ireland was a part of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and was represented in the British Parliament by 105 Members of Parliament (MPs).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Whereas in Great Britain most elected politicians were members of either the Liberal Party or the Conservative Party, from the early 1880s most Irish MPs were Irish nationalists, who sat together in the British House of Commons as the Irish Parliamentary Party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP strove for Home Rule, that is, limited self-government for Ireland within the United Kingdom, and had been supported by most Irish people, especially the Catholic majority.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule was opposed by most Protestants in Ireland, who formed a majority of the population in parts of the northern province of Ulster but a minority in the rest of Ireland, and favoured maintenance of the Union with Great Britain (and were therefore called Unionists).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionists were supported by the Conservative Party, whereas from 1885 the Liberal Party was committed to enacting some form of Home Rule.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists eventually formed their own representation, first the Irish Unionist Party then the Ulster Unionist Party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule appeared to have been finally achieved with the passing of the Home Rule Act 1914.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the implementation of the Act was temporarily postponed with the outbreak of World War I due to determined Ulster Unionists' resistance to the Act.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As the war prolonged and with the failure to make any progress on the issue, the more radical Sinn Féin began to grow in strength.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin was founded by Arthur Griffith in 1905.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He believed that Irish nationalists should emulate the *Ausgleich* of Hungarian nationalists who, in the 19th century under Ferenc Deák, had chosen to boycott the imperial parliament in Vienna and unilaterally established their own legislature in Budapest.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Griffith had favoured a peaceful solution based on 'dual monarchy' with Britain, that is two separate states with a single head of state and a limited central government to control matters of common concern only.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, by 1918, under its new leader Éamon de Valera, Sinn Féin had come to favour achieving separation from Britain by means of an armed uprising if necessary and the establishment of an independent republic.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the 1916 Easter Rising the party's ranks were swelled by participants and supporters of the rebellion as they were freed from British prisons and internment camps, and at its 1917 Ard Fheis (annual conference) de Valera was elected leader and the new, more radical policy adopted.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Prior to 1916, Sinn Féin had been a fringe movement having a limited cooperative alliance with William O'Brien's All-for-Ireland League and enjoyed little electoral success.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, between the Easter Rising of that year and the 1918 general election, the party's popularity increased dramatically.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin demonstrated its new electoral capability in four by-election successes in 1917 in which Count Plunkett, Joseph McGuinness, de Valera and W.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave were each elected, although it lost three by-elections in early 1918 before winning two more with Patrick McCartan and Arthur Griffith.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In one case there were unproven allegations of electoral fraud.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had benefitted from a number of factors in the 1918 elections, including demographic changes and political factors.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate in 1918, as with the entire electorate throughout the United Kingdom, had changed in two major ways since the preceding general election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Firstly, there was a "generational" change because of the First World War, which meant that the British general election due in 1915 had not taken place.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As a result, no election took place between 1910 and 1918, the longest gap in modern British and Irish constitutional history until then (it was superseded in Britain in 1935–45).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Secondly, the franchise had been greatly extended by the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This granted voting rights to women (albeit only those over 30) for the first time, and gave all men over 21 and military servicemen over 19 a vote in parliamentary elections without property qualifications.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate increased from around 700,000 to about two million.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Overall, a new generation of young voters, and the sudden influx of women over thirty, meant that vast numbers of new voters of unknown voter affiliation existed, changing dramatically the composition of the Irish electorate.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Six MPs stood under a different political affiliation from the December 1910 general election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] One MP stood under a different political affiliation from their by-election victory.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Voting in most Irish constituencies occurred on Saturday, 14 December 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] While the rest of the United Kingdom fought the 'Khaki election' on other issues involving the British parties, in Ireland four major political parties had national appeal.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] These were the IPP, Sinn Féin, the Irish Unionist Party and the Irish Labour Party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionist Party favoured continuance of the union with Britain (along with its subordinate, the Ulster Unionist Labour Association, who fought as Labour Unionists).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] A number of other small nationalist parties also took part.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ireland had 105 seats elected from 103 constituencies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ninety-nine seats were elected from single-seat geographical constituencies under the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There were two two-seat constituencies: Dublin University (Trinity College) elected two MPs under the single transferable vote and Cork City elected two MPs under the bloc voting system.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In addition to ordinary geographical constituencies there were three university constituencies: the Queen's University of Belfast (which returned a Unionist), Dublin University (which returned two Unionists) and the National University (which returned a member of Sinn Féin).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 105 seats, 25 were uncontested, with a Sinn Féin candidate winning unopposed.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Seventeen of these seats were in Munster.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In some cases it was because there was a certain winner in Sinn Féin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dillon was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1880.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He resigned in 1883 but was re-elected in 1885.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Donovan contested the Donegal South constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Esmonde was first elected to the Dublin South constituency in 1885.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell contested the Longford constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell was first elected to the Cavan West constituency in 1895.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Hazleton contested the Louth constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Kilbride was first elected to the Kerry South constituency in 1887.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He retired in 1900 but was re-elected in 1903.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Meehan contested the Queen's County constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Nugent contested the Dublin St Michan's constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1885.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1892 but regained it in 1905.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Dowd was first elected to the Sligo North constituency in 1900.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Shee contested the Waterford County constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch contested the Battersea South constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch was first elected to the Galway Borough constituency in 1901.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1903 following his conviction but was re-elected in 1909.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Stepney Limehouse constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Gwynn contested the Dublin University constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Westmeath constituency in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In this election, 75 candidates who had never previously been elected to Parliament were elected.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin candidates won 73 seats out of 105, but four party candidates (Arthur Griffith, Éamon de Valera, Eoin MacNeill and Liam Mellows) were elected for two constituencies and so the total number of individual Sinn Féin MPs elected was 69.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Despite the isolated allegations of intimidation and electoral fraud on the part of both republicans and unionists, the election was seen as a landslide victory for Sinn Féin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin received 46.9% of votes island-wide, and 65% of votes in the area that became the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the 46.9% is not the total result of the overall success of Sinn Féin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That figure only accounts for 48 seats that they won because in 25 of the other constituencies the other parties did not contest them, and Sinn Féin won them unopposed.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Most of these constituencies were Sinn Féin strongholds.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It has been estimated that, had the 25 seats been contested, Sinn Féin would have received at least 53% of the vote island-wide.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, this is a conservative estimate and the percentage would likely have been higher.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin also did not contest four seats due to a deal with the IPP (see below).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Labour, who had pulled out in the south under instructions to 'wait', polled better in Belfast than Sinn Féin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Within the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, Sinn Féin achieved 400,269 votes in the contested seats out of 606,117 total votes cast which amounted to a huge landslide of 66.0% in the vote and winning 70 out of the 75 constituencies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Unionist Party won 22 seats and 25.3% of the vote island-wide (29.2% when Labour Unionist candidates are included), becoming the second-largest party in terms of MPs.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The success of the unionists, who won 26 seats overall, was largely limited to Ulster.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Otherwise, southern unionists were elected only in the constituencies of Rathmines and Dublin University which returned two.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that later became the Irish Free State and then the Republic of Ireland, the Irish Unionist Alliance polled 37,218 votes from 101,839 total votes cast for other parties in the constituencies that they stood a candidate.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, if all of the total votes in the contested seats where the Irish Unionist Alliance did not stand are included there was a total of 606,117 votes cast, which converts the Irish Unionist Alliance share of the vote in the 26 counties to just 6.1%.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] With the one Independent Unionist being elected for Dublin University adding 0.1% in total with 793 votes to give 6.2% across the 26 counties and only 3 seats won by the Unionists.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP suffered a catastrophic defeat including the loss of its leader, John Dillon.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It won only six seats in Ireland, its losses exaggerated by the "first-past-the-post" system which gave it a share of seats far short of its much larger share of the vote (21.7%) and the number of seats it would have won under a "proportional representation" ballot system.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] All but one of its seats were in Ulster.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The exception was Waterford City, the seat previously held by John Redmond, who had died earlier in the year, and retained by his son Captain William Redmond.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Four of their Ulster seats were part of the deal to avoid unionist victories which saved some for the party but may have cost it the support of Protestant voters elsewhere.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP came close to winning other seats in County Louth and Wexford South, and in general their support held up better in the north and east of the island.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party was represented in Westminster by seven MPs because T.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor won the Liverpool Scotland seat he had held since the 1885 election due to Irish emigrant votes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The remnants of the IPP in time became the Nationalist Party of Northern Ireland under the leadership of Joseph Devlin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, the Irish Parliamentary Party won 181,320 votes out of 606,117 total votes cast in the contested seats, amounting to a 26.0% vote share.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] If the Independent Home Rule Nationalists are included there were 11,162 votes which comes to 1.8% and a vote share of 27.8% for the Nationalists.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Parliamentary Party held on to just 2 seats in the 26 counties that became Southern Ireland and then the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster (nine counties), Unionists won 23 out of the 38 seats with Sinn Féin gaining ten and the Irish Parliamentary Party five.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was a limited electoral pact brokered by Roman Catholic Cardinal Michael Logue in December between Sinn Féin and the Nationalist IPP in eight seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, it only concluded after nominations closed.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin instructed its supporters to vote IPP in Armagh South, despite no Unionist candidate (79 SF votes), Down South (33 SF votes for Éamon de Valera), Tyrone North-East (56 SF votes) and Donegal East (46 SF votes).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP instructed its supporters to vote Sinn Féin in Fermanagh South (132 IPP votes) which had no Unionist candidate, Londonderry City (120 IPP votes) where Eoin MacNeill narrowly beat the Unionist, and Tyrone North-West also against a Unionist but where no IPP candidate was nominated.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The discipline of voters, when faced with two rival nationalist candidates and with only a post-nomination pact, was impressive.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The pact only broke down in Down East where a Unionist won as the IPP candidate refused to participate, thus splitting the Catholic nationalist vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was no pact in Belfast Falls which Joe Devlin (IPP) won with 8,488 votes against 3,245 for Éamon de Valera (SF) although no Unionist stood.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The only other Belfast seat contested by both nationalist parties was Duncairn against Edward Carson; otherwise, Sinn Féin stood alone in seven seats reaching double figures in two.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Monaghan North was won by Sinn Féin's Ernest Blythe in a three-cornered fight against both IPP and Unionist candidates.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the Monaghan South, and Donegal North, South and West seats, despite no Unionist standing, Sinn Féin won all four against IPP candidates.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin took the two (uncontested) Cavan seats with Arthur Griffith taking his second in Cavan East as well as that of Tyrone North West.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In six contested seats no Unionist stood.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists won a clear majority of the 38 Ulster seats including eight of the nine in Belfast.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the six Ulster counties which formed the future Northern Ireland, Unionists won 23 of the 30 seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On 21 January 1919, 27 (out of 101 elected) members representing thirty constituencies answered the roll of Dáil Éireann—the Irish for "Assembly of Ireland".
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Invitations to attend the Dáil had been sent to all 100 men and one woman who had been elected on 14 December 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Eoin MacNeill had been elected for both Londonderry City and the National University of Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Thirty-three republicans were unable to attend as they were in prison, most of them without trial since 17 May 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Pierce McCan (of Tipperary East), who died in prison, would have brought the total to thirty-four.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 69 republicans elected, most had fought in the Easter Rising.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In accordance with the Sinn Féin manifesto, their elected members refused to attend Westminster, having instead formed their own parliament.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dáil Éireann was, according to John Patrick McCarthy, the revolutionary government under which the Irish War of Independence was fought and which sought international recognition.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Maryann Gialanella Valiulis says that having justified its existence, the Dáil provided itself with a theoretical framework and set about the process of state-building.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] After having dominated Irish politics for four decades, the IPP was so decimated by its massive defeat that it dissolved soon after the election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As mentioned above, its remains became the Northern Ireland-based Nationalist Party, which survived in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The British administration and unionists refused to recognise the Dáil.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] At its first meeting attended by 27 deputies (others were still imprisoned or impaired) on 21 January 1919 the Dáil issued a Declaration of Independence and proclaimed itself the parliament of a new state, the Irish Republic.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On the same day, in unconnected circumstances, two members of the Royal Irish Constabulary guarding gelignite were killed in the Soloheadbeg Ambush by members of the Irish Volunteers.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Although it had not ordered this incident, the course of events soon drove the Dáil to recognise the Volunteers as the army of the Irish Republic and the ambush as an act of war against Great Britain.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Volunteers therefore changed their name, in August, to the Irish Republican Army.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The train of events set in motion by the elections would eventually bring about the creation of the Irish Free State as a British dominion in 1922.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That state became the first internationally recognised independent Irish state in 1931, when the Statute of Westminster removed virtually all of the UK Parliament's remaining authority over the Free State and the other dominions.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Free State eventually evolved into the modern Republic of Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The leaders of the Sinn Féin candidates elected in 1918, such as de Valera, Michael Collins and W.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave, came to dominate Irish politics.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] De Valera, for example, would hold some form of elected office from his first election as an MP in a by-election in 1917 until 1973.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The two major parties in the Republic of Ireland today, Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael, are both descendants of Sinn Féin, which first enjoyed substantial electoral success in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Elections were held in January and June 1920 for the various county and district councils of Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The elections were organised by the Dublin Castle administration under the law of the then United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland (UK), and held while the Irish War of Independence was pitting UK forces against those of the Irish Republic proclaimed in 1919 by the First Dáil.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Elections were held in two stages: borough and urban district councils in January; and county and rural district councils in June.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Sinn Féin, which had established the First Dáil, won control of many of the councils, which subsequently broke contact with Dublin Castle's Local Government Board for Ireland and instead recognised the republican Department of Local Government.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The next local elections were held in 1924 in Northern Ireland and in 1925 in the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] In the 1918 general elections the newly reformed Sinn Féin party had secured a large majority of Irish seats in the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Many of the seats won by Sinn Féin were uncontested and thus were secured by acclamation.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Where the seats were contested, the elections used the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Those two reasons explain how the Sinn Féin took a majority of seats in the chamber even though in the districts where the seat was *contested* the party received less than half the vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The Bill's second reading debate and vote were on 24 March.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The government hoped that the new system would reveal less-than-monolithic support for Sinn Féin, and it was first tested in the 1920 local elections.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Some Sinn Féin members including Arthur Griffith had also helped to form the Proportional Representation Society of Ireland in the different circumstances of 1911.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] By 1920 the party was in a far stronger electoral position, and had no reason to oppose proportional representation, and it treated these elections as internal Irish elections for local authorities that were expected to swear allegiance to the new Irish Republic.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] STV, the electoral system introduced by the 1919 Act, is still used today in elections in the Republic of Ireland and most elections in Northern Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The 1919 act mandated elections for all urban councils except Sligo Corporation, which had been reconstituted and elected in 1919.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The 15 January elections saw Sinn Féin, Labour, and other nationalists winning control of 172 of Ireland's 206 borough and urban district councils.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The subsequent mayoral elections on 30 January saw a Unionist elected for Belfast, a Nationalist in Derry, Labour in Wexford, and Sinn Féin in eight boroughs.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] In Westport, only 4 candidates were nominated for the 18 seats on the urban district council, and only 2 of those accepted office.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Since 5 councillors was a quorum, Mayo County Council mandated a special election for 15 March, but only one extra candidate was nominated.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The rural elections showed a much greater level of support for Sinn Féin in its core support area.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] It took control of 338 out of 393 local government bodies, county councils, boards of guardians and rural district councils across the whole island.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] The county and rural district elections saw virtually no contests outside of Ulster.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Sinn Féin's success gave them dominance in virtually every county council and rural district council outside of Ulster.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1920-irish-local-elections] Sinn Féin success in 12 June rural and county elections extended even to Ulster, with the party winning control of 36 of Ulsters 55 rural districts.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] General elections took place in Ireland on 24 May 1921 to elect members of the House of Commons of Northern Ireland and the House of Commons of Southern Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] These legislatures had been established by the Government of Ireland Act 1920, which granted Home Rule to a partitioned Ireland within the United Kingdom.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] The Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) won a landslide majority in Northern Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] In the area designated as Southern Ireland, Sinn Féin candidates were elected unopposed in 124 of the 128 seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Only the Northern Ireland House of Commons actually sat as a functional body; the Sinn Féin candidates elected across Ireland boycotted both institutions, and instead assembled as the 2nd Dáil.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] On 21 January 1919, the Sinn Féin MPs elected to the British House of Commons at the 1918 general election met as Dáil Éireann and declared independence from the United Kingdom.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] This declaration was followed by the Irish War of Independence, which continued until a truce in July 1921.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] In November 1920, the British Parliament passed the Government of Ireland Act 1920.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] This partitioned Ireland into two distinct polities, each with their own Home Rule Parliament: Northern Ireland and Southern Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Both parliaments would be composed of a directly elected House of Commons and an indirectly elected Senate, with both lower chambers being elected by the Single Transferable Vote system of proportional representation.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] O'Connor both agreed that the Irish Party should not fight Sinn Féin for seats for the Southern parliament as things stood.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Former Irish Parliamentary Party MP Stephen Gwynn, now a member of the Irish Dominion League, advocated putting up League candidates against Sinn Féin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] In early March he met with southern Unionists Viscount Midleton and Lord Oranmore, requesting them to pool their resources to contest the election and contest the election on a platform opposing the IRA's violence, under Midleton's leadership.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Midleton declined the invitation, just as he had declined a previous request for his Unionist Anti-Partition League to join the Dominion League.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] In the area designated as Southern Ireland, no actual polling took place as all 128 candidates were returned unopposed.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Of these, 124 were won by Sinn Féin and four by independent Unionists representing Dublin University (Trinity College).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] A single Unionist candidate had been selected to contest the constituency of Donegal: Major Robert L Moore, who had contested East Donegal in 1918.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Moore however later withdrew his candidacy just before the election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] The general election to the Northern Ireland House of Commons occurred on Tuesday, 24 May.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Of 52 seats, including Queen's University of Belfast, 40 were won by Unionists, 6 by the Nationalist Party and 6 by Sinn Féin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Several well known republicans were elected: Éamon de Valera for South Down, Michael Collins for Armagh, Eoin MacNeill for Derry and Arthur Griffith for Fermanagh and Tyrone.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Voters in Fermanagh and Tyrone returned an anti-partition majority of 7,831.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Allegations were made claiming intimidation of Nationalist voters, arrests of candidates/organisers and the seizure of electoral literature.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] Although the elections were formally for two separate legislatures, Irish republicans considered all those elected to be members of the 2nd Dáil.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] In practice, however, the Dáil was composed of 125 Sinn Féin members.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] The Unionist and Nationalist Party members ignored the invitation to attend the Dáil, while the four independent unionists assembled as the Southern Ireland Commons for a single brief meeting.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] The Northern Ireland House of Commons continued to function as a Home Rule legislature until it was abolished in 1973.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1921-northern-ireland-and-southern-ireland-general-elections] The Southern Ireland Commons was largely ignored, and only formally met twice: first in a brief 1921 session that only the four unionists attended, and then again in 1922 to approve the Anglo-Irish Treaty which established the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The **1922 Irish general election** took place in Southern Ireland on Friday, 16 June.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The election was separately called by a resolution of Dáil Éireann on 19 May and by an order of the Provisional Government on 27 May.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The body elected was thus both the 3rd Dáil and provisional parliament replacing the parliament of Southern Ireland, under the provisions of the 1921 Anglo-Irish Treaty to elect a constituent assembly paving the way for the formal establishment of the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] From 6 December 1922, it continued as the Dáil Éireann of the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The election was held under the electoral system of proportional representation by means of the single transferable vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] It was the first contested general election held in the jurisdiction using the STV system.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The election was held in the 128 seats using the constituencies designated to the Southern Ireland House of Commons in the Government of Ireland Act 1920.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Under this Act, constituencies ranged in size from 3 to 8 seats, the largest being the eight seat Kerry–Limerick West and Cork Mid.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] In the 1921 elections, Sinn Féin had won all seats in uncontested elections, except for the four in the Dublin University constituency.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] On this occasion, however, most seats were contested.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The treaty had divided the party between 65 pro-treaty candidates, 57 anti-treaty and 1 nominally on both sides.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] To minimise losses due to competition from other parties, Éamon de Valera and Michael Collins worked out a pact approved on 20 May 1922.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] They agreed that the pro-treaty and anti-treaty factions would fight the general election jointly and form a coalition government afterwards.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The sitting member would not be opposed by the other faction.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] This pact prevented voters giving their opinions on the treaty itself, especially in uncontested seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] However, the draft Constitution of the Irish Free State was then published on 15 June, and so the anti-treaty Sinn Féin group's 36 seats out of 128 seemed to many to be a democratic endorsement of the pro-treaty Sinn Féin's arrangements.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Others argued that insufficient time was available to understand the draft constitution, but the main arguments and debates had already been made public during and after the Dáil Treaty Debates that had ended on 10 January 1922, nearly six months before.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Winston Churchill, the Secretary of State for the Colonies, opposed the Pact as undemocratic, and made a long statement on 31 May.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] He was responsible at the time for steering the transitional arrangements between the Provisional Government and the government of the United Kingdom in the period between the ratification of the Treaty and the creation of the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Despite the Pact, the election results started the effective division of Sinn Féin into separate parties.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The anti-Treaty TDs boycotted the new Dáil, even though they had requested, negotiated and approved the terms of the Pact.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] This boycott gave control of the Dáil to the pro-Treaty members of Sinn Féin, and so enabled W.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Cosgrave to establish the Second Provisional Government.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The First Executive Council of the Irish Free State was appointed on 6 December 1922 on the nomination of this Dáil.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Many seats were won unopposed; 17 by Pro-Treaty Sinn Féin, 16 by Anti-Treaty Sinn Féin and 4 by independents.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Each party's seat share was within seven percent points of its vote share percentage.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Out of a valid poll of 621,587 votes, the pro-Treaty faction of Sinn Féin won 239,195 votes and the anti-Treaty faction won 135,310 votes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The other parties and independents (see above) all supported the Treaty and secured a further 247,080 votes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Further, the anti-Treaty candidates had taken part in an election in line with Article 11 of the Treaty, even though they had argued that it was flawed, being partitionist.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Their pro-Treaty opponents argued that this revealed that their anti-Treaty stance was opportunist, and not principled.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Article 11 of the Treaty had limited such an election to the constituencies of the formative Free State, and specifically excluded constituencies in Northern Ireland, yet the anti-Treaty argument was that the Dáil represented the whole island of Ireland.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Within 12 days, on 28 June 1922, as a result of the tensions between pro- and anti-Treatyites, the Irish Civil War broke out, when the Provisional Government's troops began a bombardment of the Anti-Treaty IRA's occupation of the Four Courts, Dublin.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] The Dáil had been due to convene on 1 July, but its opening was prorogued on 5 occasions, meeting on 9 September 1922.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Michael Collins and Arthur Griffith, leaders of two separate but co-operating administrations, had respectively been killed and had died in August.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] Cosgrave, leader of the pro-Treaty Sinn Féin TDs, was elected as President of Dáil Éireann and formed the 5th Ministry of Dáil Éireann.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] On 6 December 1922, on the establishment of the Irish Free State, Cosgrave was nominated by the Dáil to the position of President of the Executive Council, and was appointed by the Governor-General Tim Healy.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] He formed the 1st Executive Council of the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] As each constituency was a multi-seat contest, rows represent changes in the constituency as a whole, rather than between individual TDs.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1922-irish-general-election] TD who contested 1922 election under a different affiliation to 1921.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] The **1923 Irish general election** to elect the 4th Dáil was held on Monday, 27 August, following the dissolution of the 3rd Dáil on 9 August 1923.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] It was the first general election held since the establishment of the Irish Free State on 6 December 1922.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] The election was held shortly after the end of the Irish Civil War in May 1923.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] Many of the Republican TDs, who represented the losing anti-Treaty side, were still imprisoned during and after the election and had committed to not participating in the Dáil if elected.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] The 4th Dáil assembled at Leinster House on 19 September to nominate the President of the Executive Council and Executive Council of the Irish Free State for appointment by the Governor-General.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] Cumann na nGaedheal, the successor to the Pro-Treaty wing of Sinn Féin, won the election and formed the government.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] Despite falling 14 seats of an outright majority, the opposition Republican TDs refused to take their seats, giving CnG effective control of the chamber and allowing it to form what amounted to a majority government.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] It was the first general election fought since the establishment of the Irish Free State and the adoption of the Constitution of the Irish Free State on 6 December 1922.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] It was contested under the Electoral Act 1923, which increased the seats in the Dáil from 128 to 153, and introduced a franchise of all citizens over the age of 21, without distinction of sex.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] Lax electoral practices were tightened up by The Prevention of Electoral Abuses Act 1923.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] Most parties made gains, in part because the total number of seats in the Dáil was increased by 25 from 128 to 153.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] The Republican TDs continued to abstain from the Dáil.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1923-irish-general-election] Therefore, Cumann na nGaedheal had a majority of seats which were taken in the Dáil and formed the 2nd Executive Council of the Irish Free State on 19 September 1923.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-irish-local-elections] The **1925 Irish local elections** were the first local elections following the establishment of the Irish Free State.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-irish-local-elections] The Local Government Act 1925 had abolished rural district councils, passing their powers to Ireland's various county councils.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-irish-local-elections] Elections did not place in all councils, with a number of councils being dissolved by W.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-irish-local-elections] Cosgraves Cumann na nGaedheal government in 1923 and 1924, either due to being controlled by anti-Treaty politicians during the Irish Civil War, or because of alleged financial mismanagement.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-irish-local-elections] These councils instead were run by appointed commissioners.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] An election for 19 of the 60 seats in Seanad Éireann, the senate of the Irish Free State, was held on 17 September 1925.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The election was by single transferable vote, with the entire country being used as a 19-seat constituency.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The election saw eight Cumann na nGaedheal members elected (an advance of one compared to its pre-election representation), as well as three Labour Party (a drop of one seat), three Farmers' Party (an advance of two seats), and five others (a drop from seven previous to the election).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] There were 76 candidates on the ballot paper.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Voters ranked candidates by preference at least a few, but did not have to rank all of them.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Although bearing multiple marked preferences, each vote was to be used to elect just one member in the end.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Of the two main political parties, the larger (Cumann na nGaedheal) did not formally endorse any candidates, while the other (Sinn Féin, whose TDs were abstentionist) boycotted the election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Voter turnout was low, and the outcome was considered unsatisfactory by some.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] In subsequent elections, senators were elected by the members of the Oireachtas rather than by the electorate.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The 1922 Constitution of the Irish Free State provided for a Seanad of 60 members directly elected.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Members would serve 12-year terms, with one-quarter of the house elected every three years.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The members would be elected under the system of proportional representation by means of the single transferable vote in a single, nationwide, 15-seat contest.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] As well as this cohort up for election in 1925, four additional Senators were required to vacate their seats: these had been temporarily co-opted to fill casual vacancies that had arisen in previous years.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The 60 Senators were divided into four cohorts of 15, and an at-large election held every three years for one of the cohorts.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] As part of the initial transitional measures, 30 of the 60 Senators elected in 1922 were selected by the Dáil, of whom the last 15 to secure election formed the cohort whose term would end in 1925, the end of the first triennial period established by the 1922 constitution.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] There were three methods of being included on the ballot.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Outgoing Senators could nominate themselves for re-election, and all 19 did so.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The Seanad could nominate a number of candidates equal to the number of vacancies (19), and the Dáil could nominate twice the number of vacancies (38).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The Dáil and Seanad nominations were by single transferable vote and secret ballot.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The minimum age for Senators was 35 years.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The Seanad resolved on 30 April to form a committee to decide procedure for its nominations; the committee drafted a resolution in June, which was amended and passed by the Seanad on 19 June.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] 29 applicants contested the Seanad nominations on 1 July.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Apart from two Labour Party members, the candidates were Independents.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] 47 of the 60 Senators voted, including 18 of the 19 who were themselves standing for re-election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Donal O'Sullivan, clerk of the Seanad throughout its existence, suggests that these 18 had an incentive to vote for less popular candidates since the nominees would be rivals in the ensuing election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] O'Sullivan describes the results as "a very great disappointment ... the list [of successful nominees] could not compare with the list of the ten rejected." Oliver St.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] John Gogarty made a similar remark in the Seanad itself after the results were announced.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Cumann na nGaedheal, the party which backed the incumbent government, decided not to formally support any candidates as a result of internal divisions.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] There was tension between ministers, backbenchers, and grassroots members, and between factions of Kevin O'Higgins and W.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The 1924 Army Mutiny had shaken the year-old party, and the appointment of public servants to lead the new state's institutions created resentment among those passed over.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The parliamentary party held two selection conventions, on 2 and 6 July 1925, and when the leadership's candidates did badly a free vote was offered in the Dáil with all candidates nominally endorsed by the party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The Dáil nominations were decided on 8 July.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] 57 candidates contested; 101 TDs voted, with one ballot deemed ineligible.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] 52 TDs did not vote, including all 44 abstentionist Sinn Féin TDs, who were ineligible to vote as they had not taken the Oath of Allegiance.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] TDs supported candidates on party lines.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Of the 38 successful nominees, O'Sullivan classifies 21 as supporters of the Cumann na nGaedheal Government, 9 as Independent, 5 as in the Farmers' Party, and 3 as in the Labour Party.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Four of the ten candidates rejected by the Seanad were also among the Dáil candidates, with John J.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Horgan securing a nomination at the second attempt.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The usual Irish local, personal canvassing strategy was impractical across a nationwide constituency, leading to a relatively quiet campaign.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] While the Farmers' Party and Labour produced newspaper advertisements for their respective slates of candidates, Cumann na nGaedheal did not at a national level formally endorse candidates, even those its TDs had nominated.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] It presented the election as nonpartisan.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] It published a booklet, *Who's who in the 1925 Senate Election*, and did not oppose candidates "put forward by any of the elements that accept the State and Constitution", i.e. other than republicans opposed to the Anglo-Irish Treaty.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Numerous interest groups produced lists of approved candidates, including doctors, publicans, motorists, ex-servicemen's associations, and the livestock trade.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Candidates endorsed by temperance groups fared badly.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The Catholic Truth Society circulated, to little effect, a list of outgoing Senators it condemned for not having opposed a controversial motion pertaining to divorce.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Sinn Féin, under the leadership of Éamon de Valera, called for a boycott of the election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Sinn Féin had not boycotted the 1923 Dáil election, but rather contested it on an abstentionist platform.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] De Valera later led the new Fianna Fáil party, founded in 1926, into the Oireachtas after the June 1927 Dáil election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The election was by single transferable vote, with the entire Irish Free State forming a single, 19-seat constituency.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Since the voting age for Dáil and local elections was 21, a separate electoral roll was maintained for the Seanad election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The 76 candidates were arranged alphabetically on a ballot paper 22 inches (56 cm) long and 16 inches (41 cm) wide.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The Electoral (Seanad Elections) Act 1925 was passed to allow the ballot to be presented as four parallel columns of 19 names rather than a single long column of all 76.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The low voter turnout was blamed on the Sinn Féin boycott, wet weather across the country, and the shorter than usual hours of polling.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Turnout varied widely, from 8.2% in Mayo North to 43% in Monaghan.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The ballots were initially collected to one centre within each Dáil constituency to count and sort the first-preference votes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] On 25 September, the ballots were sent to Dublin, the totals checked centrally, and redistribution of transfers begun.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Initially there were 10 count officials, rising to 40 by the end.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] On 5 October, the first candidate was returned, on the 45th count.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Harold Gosnell wrote that there was more news coverage of the count than of the preceding campaign: "the counting of the ballots under [STV] applied on a national scale attracts wide attention, and the results are sure to reflect the opinions (or lack of them) manifested by the electors".
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Although the election was national, many of the candidates relied on local support: 23 gained more than half their first preferences from their own constituency.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Thus, STV proved itself both able to elect those with local support and those with thinly-spread dispersed support.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] About 12% (37,714) of valid ballots were exhausted, found to be non-transferable when eligible for transfer.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] (One or more of the preferences marked on the ballots may have been elected, just without the help of that particular vote).
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Less than 3 percent of the ballots cast were spoiled.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] About 260,000 of the 315,000 votes cast were used in the end to elect the 19 winners, an 85 percent rate of effective votes.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Candidates of the two parties contesting the election, the Labour Party and the Farmers' Party, did relatively well.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Some interest groups also did well – vintners, ex-servicemen.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Others did not — doctors, academics, women, and especially Irish language revivalists: all four candidates supported by the Gaelic League lost, including outgoing Senator and future president Douglas Hyde.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] 24, 1925) reported that licensed liquor dealers, ex-soldiers, farmers, doctors and businessmen received their due in the election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Ex-Unionist candidates did not fare well, even though the original design of the Seanad was intended in part to provide enhanced representation for the Unionist minority.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] The quota (the amount guaranteed to secure election) was 15,286.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1925-seanad-election] Thirteen were elected at the end, when the field of candidates was thinned to the number of remaining open seats in the 65th count, some of them were elected with less than the quota.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] The **1989 European Parliament election in Ireland** was the Irish component of the 1989 European Parliament election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland/1989-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] The election was conducted under the single transferable vote.
